lopedia Britannica}}</ref> This strategy has not always proven successful, as President [[Gerald Ford]] nearly [[1976 Republican National Convention|lost the nomination]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/the-buzz/ronald-reagan-vs-gerald-ford-the-1976-gop-convention-battle-15818|title=Ronald Reagan vs. Gerald Ford: The 1976 GOP Convention Battle Royal|first=Lee|last=Edwards|date=April 16, 2016|website=The National Interest}}</ref> in the 1976 primaries and President [[George H.W. Bush]] was challenged in [[1992 Republican Party presidential primaries|1992]].\n\nIn December 2018, the Trump campaign announced that it was merging its field operations with that of the Republican National Committee's.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/12/18/politics/trump-2020-campaign-rnc/index.html|title=Trump gears up for 2020 re-election by tightening grip on party|author=Dan Merica|website=Cnn.com|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}</ref> The following month at the RNC's winter meeting in New Mexico, while acknowledging that declaring the President the party's provisional nominee would break FEC rules, the RNC voted to endorse him informally by voting to give him its \"full support.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2019/jan/26/rnc-vote-unanimous-support-trump-no-endorse-2020/|title=RNC unanimously pledges 'undivided support' for Trump, stops short of explicit 2020 endorsement|first=Andrew|last=Blake|date=January 26, 2019|publisher=The Washington Times|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== United States presidents ===\n\n===U.S. Executive Branch officials===\n====Current====\n[[File:Mike Pence official Vice Presidential portrait (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|[[Mike Pence]]]]\n[[File:Ben_Carson_official_portrait.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Ben Carson]]]]\n[[File:Nikki Haley official photo.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Nikki Haley]]]]\n* [[Mike Pence]], [[Vice President of the United States]] 2017\u2013present; [[Governor of Indiana|Governor]] of [[Indiana]] 2013\u20132017; [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Indiana's 6th congressional district|IN-6]] 2001\u20132013<ref name=PenceDecline>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/washington/la-na-essential-washington-updates-pence-deems-report-of-2020-presidential-1502035646-htmlstory.html|title=Vice president vehemently denies laying groundwork for potential 2020 White House bid|date=August 6, 2017|first=Laura|last=King|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Ben Carson]], [[United States Secretary of Housing and Urban Development|U.S. Secretary of Housing and Urban Development]] 2017\u2013present; [[Ben Carson presidential campaign, 2016|candidate]] for President in [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2016|2016]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/politics/wp/2017/08/23/why-ben-carsons-appearance-in-phoenix-was-likely-a-violation-of-federal-law/|title=Why Ben Carson's appearance in Phoenix was likely a violation of federal law|date=August 23, 2017|first=Philip|last=Bump|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=September 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Former====\n* [[Nikki Haley]], [[U.S. Ambassador to the United Nations]] 2017\u20132018; [[Governor of South Carolina|Governor]] of [[South Carolina]] 2011\u20132017<ref>{{cite web |last1=March |first1=Mary Tyler |title=Haley says she'll campaign for Trump in 2020 |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/410548-haley-says-shell-campaign-for-trump-in-2020 |website=TheHill |language=en |date=October 9, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Steve Bannon]], [[White House Chief Strategist]] in 2017<ref>{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/87b52f8ea4874ed8a408927c12b12149|title=Steve Bannon wants GOP to rally behind Trump|date=August 20, 2018|agency=Associated Press|last1=Lucey|first1=Catherine}}</ref>\n* [[Katie Walsh (politician)|Katie Walsh]], [[White House Deputy Chief of Staff]] for Implementation in 2017<ref name=TrumpFamilyRNC>{{cite web|url=https